Prologue
"Please!" pleaded Queen Eirwen. "Don't send her back! She's just a child!" The King of Ice looked down at his wife from his throne, his royal advisor standing beside him. She had given birth to a daughter. He frowned at the thought.
The little girl looked very much like her mother: pale blue eyes, white hair streaked with blue. The King of Ice thought a daughter would make him look weak. After all, he had only had sons up until now.
"Your only options are to kill your child or send her back into the wild. It's her punishment for your bad behavior, Eirwen." He spat her name as if it were poison. He always did that.
Frostwell was not always a single kingdom. It had been split into two, the North and the South. In the North, the non-magical kingdom. In the South, a kingdom filled with fantastical representations of power. Due to the greed of the North, the two kingdoms had torn each other apart in an endless war, until the South proposed a truce.
The South was cornered, and its royal family would do anything to stop the bloodshed. They proposed that their only princess become the queen of the North and take a son destined to be the future king. Then, the South would ally with the North to form a single kingdom. The North had accepted, and Princess Eirwen had married Prince Akull.
"I beg you, my lord, in exchange for the life of my child, do with me as you please, imprison me, banish me, or even, kill me," pleaded Queen Eirwen, holding her child tightly in her arms.
The King of Ice looked down at his wife, disgust in his eyes. Perhaps, perhaps he would have mercy on her. The one with whom he had lived for twenty-two years, who had always cared for him in his darkest hours, who had given birth to his sons.
"Very well, the child may live in the palace," he began, drawing a sigh of relief from his wife. "However," he added, "you will be executed."
The advisor and Queen Eirwen herself exchanged a horrified look. She slowly lowered her gaze. "Yes, Your Highness," she said, bowing.
The King of Frost commanded the royal advisor to take the child to one of Eirwen's empty apartments. Once this was done, he ordered the guards to lead Eirwen to the execution site, where all the villagers could witness the spectacle.
As the guards escorted her to the site, the villagers cried out in outrage at seeing their only queen, the kindest, about to be killed. Some wept, others screamed and tried to attack the guards, while others wondered what was happening, but all were outraged.
"Free her!"
"Why are they doing this to her?"
As Eirwen approached the wooden gallows, the most feared person in the kingdom entered. The user of fire. The former queen Eirwen was about to be burned alive. No one deserved such a death, not even criminals. It was the cruellest punishment in Frostfell.
Eirwen was tied to the gallows, and the king began to explain how the queen had betrayed them all. The people of Frostfell refused to believe him and never accepted his words. Then, the User of Fire burned the gallows, and a single tear rolled down the cheek of the former queen.
"Survive, Kari." That was the end of Queen Eirwen's reign.
Silence in the corridors
Tap, tap, tap. These were the only sounds coming from the farthest room on the left side of the always-frozen palace's southern wing. The servants passing by always wondered what was inside that room, afraid of what might be found within. The rumors of the maids danced through the corridors. It was believed that the late wife of the King of Ice, Eirwen, was in that room, waiting to be freed.
"They couldn't be more wrong," thought Ivory as she walked toward the southern wing, while the servants went back and forth murmuring to each other. They don't at all know what is in that room.
Of course, these rumors also applied to her, because she was the only person allowed to enter the room.
Toc Toc. "Miss Kari, are you there?"; murmured Ivory at the finely decorated door, covered in snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
She wondered if she would invite her in, unlike the other times when she had asked. I still have bruises from the last time. Ivory giggled at the memory. Kari had thrown a book at her shoulder, but when she realized who it was, she immediately apologized.
A single knock came from inside, which seemed to mean that she was there, but after all, where else could she have been?
"May I enter?"; asked Ivory, remembering the time when she had entered without asking for permission.
A knock came from inside. It seemed to want to say yes. Ivory shivered, from the cold, but also because of the noise. It was weird for Ivory to hear noise coming from a room supposed to be empty, even though Iel had entered this room for years.
"Here I am," said Ivory, opening the door slowly. The scene inside the room was unusual, according to normal people's standards, but not unexpected. There were papers everywhere. Books were scattered, the desk was broken, and a multitude of ice statues were scattered around. The room had no windows and almost no light. It was colder than the rest of the palace (and that was saying something). A snowstorm seemed to have hit inside.
The girl inside was curled up on her bed, wrapped in her blanket, reading one of her notebooks.
"Which notebook is it?" asked Ivory, sitting next to Kari on her bed.
